    "reasoning": "Problem 1: Given f(1)=2 and f(f(n))=f(n)+n, we compute sequentially: f(2)=f(f(1))=f(1)+1=3; f(3)=f(f(2))=f(2)+2=5; f(5)=f(f(3))=f(3)+3=8; f(8)=f(f(5))=f(5)+5=13. Thus k=f(8)-12=13-12=1.\n\nProblem 2: Let M=max{x_j}. For large n, the sum S_n=∑ j x_j^n is dominated by terms with x_j=M. Setting J={j: x_j=M} and S=∑_{j∈J} j, we have S_n=S M^n+T_n, where T_n is the rest. Since S_n=a_n^{n+1}+1, growth rates force a_n=M for large n, so S_n=M^{n+1}+1. Then S M^n+T_n=M^{n+1}+1 ⇒ T_n=M^n(M-S)+1. To avoid exponential growth mismatch, we must have M=S, so T_n=1 for large n. Since T_n is a sum of nonnegative terms, this forces all x_j for j∉J to be 1 and ∑_{j∉J} j=1. The only way is that the complement of J is {1}, so J={2,...,2011}, x_1=1, and x_j=M for j∈J. Then M=∑_{j=2}^{2011} j=(2011*2012/2)-1=2023065. Checking, S_n=1+M·M^n=M^{n+1}+1 for all n, so the condition holds. Thus the unique sequence is x_1=1, x_j=2023065 for j=2,...,2011.",
